<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900827-0078</DOCNO><DOCID>900827-0078.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor:   Apartheid Is   Not Capitalism</HL><DATE>08/27/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11</SO><CO>   AFRIC</CO><IN>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)</IN><LP>   Your July 30 article &quot;In South Africa, Communists' PactWith ANC Comes Under Pressure&quot; quotes Jay Naidoo of theCongress of South African Trade Unions as saying at a SouthAfrican Communist Party rally, &quot;Apartheid has been proven tobe the most brutal and inhuman form of capitalism the worldhas ever seen.&quot; This is an irresponsible and erroneousstatement, however emotionally appealing.   Prior to the advent of legal apartheid, black SouthAfrican workers and farmers were competing successfully withtheir white counterparts in the free-market economy. It wasbecause of this that the white government imposeddiscriminatory labor and land-owning laws, hardly adefinition of &quot;capitalism.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   What black workers and budding entrepreneurs in SouthAfrica need is not more government intrusion, but less. Tojumble labels in such an emotional way is to prepare theground for tragedy, as has been proved by the recent plethoraof collapsed state-dominated economies, not least on theAfrican continent.   Frederic Wile   New York</TEXT></DOC>